1 (3) "Child education personnel" means any individual employed by or
2 providing services to a public elementary or secondary school including but not
3 limited to teachers administrators, school counselors, school social workers, school
4 nurses, paraprofessionals, classroom aides, and school resource officers.
5 (4) "Trauma-informed practices" means policies, procedures, and
6 interactions that recognize the presence and impact of trauma and respond in ways
7 that promote student safety, empowerment, and healing while avoiding
8 re-traumatization.
9 §1300.82. Trauma-informed training program
10 A. The department shall develop a comprehensive, evidence-based,
11 statewide trauma-informed training program for child education personnel.
12 B. The training program shall satisfy all of the following requirements:
13 (1) Provide education on the prevalence and impact of adverse childhood
14 events.
15 (2) Identify common signs and symptoms of trauma in children and
16 adolescents.
17 (3) Provide strategies for responding to trauma-related behaviors in a
18 supportive and non-punitive manner.
19 (4) Promote culturally responsive and developmentally appropriate
20 approaches.
21 (5) Include guidance on referral pathways to appropriate school-based or
22 community-based mental health and support services.
23 (6) Emphasize self-care and secondary trauma prevention for educators and
24 school staff.
25 C. The department may consult with the Department of Education, child
26 welfare agencies, mental health professionals, and other relevant stakeholders in
27 developing the training curriculum.
28 D. The department may provide the training through in-person instruction
29 online modules.
